    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>Are AI stocks in a bubble in 2025?</summary>
        <p>While valuations for some pure-play AI companies are stretched, the fundamental earnings growth for infrastructure providers (like Nvidia and Microsoft) has largely supported their stock price appreciation. It is a bifurcated market requiring careful selection.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between AI hardware and AI software stocks?</summary>
        <p>AI hardware stocks (semiconductors, server racks) are the 'picks and shovels' providing the necessary infrastructure, currently capturing the majority of AI revenues. AI software stocks are building applications on top of this infrastructure, representing the next wave of monetization.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Is it too late to invest in AI stocks?</summary>
        <p>No. The transition to generative AI is considered a platform shift on par with the internet or mobile computing. While the initial infrastructure build-out phase is well underway, the software and application phases are still in their infancy.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How should a beginner invest in AI?</summary>
        <p>For beginners, the safest approach is often investing in the mega-cap tech companies (Microsoft, Alphabet, Amazon) which possess the capital and data to dominate AI, or utilizing a broad semiconductor ETF to capture the hardware growth without picking individual winners.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What are the risks of investing in AI stocks?</summary>
        <p>Key risks include intense competition leading to commoditization of AI models, massive capital expenditure requirements depressing free cash flow, potential regulatory actions regarding data privacy and copyright, and cyclical downturns in semiconductor demand.</p>
      </details>

    </section>
